  "description": "Multiplication is the operation of repeated addition — 3×43 \\times 4 means adding 3 to itself 4 times: 3+3+3+3=123 + 3 + 3 + 3 = 12. But this description, while correct for natural numbers, sells the concept short. Multiplication is the second fundamental operation of arithmetic, and its behavior — especially its interaction with addition through the distributive law — gives arithmetic its rich structure.\nIn the formal development of the natural numbers, multiplication is defined recursively using addition and the successor function: n×0=0n \\times 0 = 0 (multiplying by zero gives zero), and n×S(m)=n+(n×m)n \\times S(m) = n + (n \\times m) (multiplying by the successor of mm means adding one more copy of nn). Just as addition reduces to repeated application of the successor, multiplication reduces to repeated addition. Exponentiation, in turn, reduces to repeated multiplication — each layer of arithmetic is built from the one below.\n",
  "name": "Multiplication",
